        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1880-11-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1880-11-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="17" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <head>No. 17.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Evarts</persName>
                            to Mr. <persName type="to">Delaplaine</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                    of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1880-11-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">November</hi> 26,
                            1880</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 199.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 377, of the 26th ultimo,
                        inclosing a translation and a copy of the Hungarian law of 1879 on
                        naturalization, has been received.</p>
                <p>The view expressed to you by the chief of the judicial section of the foreign
                        office as to the applicability of the exceptions of article 47 of that law
                        to our citizens, native and naturalized, resident in Hungary, is believed to
                        be the correct and true interpretation of that article; and inasmuch as this
                        may be assumed as the proper construction of the article, <pb facs="0151" n="27" xml:id="pg_27"/> it is not deemed advisable at present, and in
                        the absence of an actual, practical question, to interrogate the imperial
                        and royal government on that point. Your care and prudence in submitting the
                        suggestion, however, is commendable.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WM. M. EVARTS.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
